Component Interaction Modes with the ARIA Application Role

02
On this page
  1. Sortable List Demo
  2. About the ARIA Application Role

Sortable List Demo

In the component sandbox there is a demo of a sortable list. The interactions for this component are limited to keyboard and screen reader support, although it would probably have drag and drop for mouse users enabled eventually as well. Starting with accessible interactions first? Yes, we can do that!

By default, the Sortable List renders in a view-only mode. When you click the "Edit gear list" button the list changes the component into an edit mode that allows for items to be arranged differently. This concept will come in handy when combining mouse drag and drop with screen reader accessible reordering.

Note that the list can only be reordered by keyboard at this point! There is no mouse functionality wired in.

In edit mode you can Tab to an item to give it focus, then change its position by using the up or down Arrow keys.

Behind the scenes, when the list is in edit mode, the ARIA role of application has been added.

About the ARIA Application Role

The purpose of role="application" is to provide a mechanism for complete control over keyboard commands in Assistive Technology. With this role, keystrokes are passed through to the browser instead of being intercepted for screen reader commands. Note that it mostly applies to Windows screen readers and should be used sparingly.

The application role causes the screen reader to stay in Focus/Forms mode, as opposed to Browse/Virtual mode found in NVDA and JAWS.

Recall using NVDA and hitting the “H” key in a previous lesson. In a text input, which automatically enters Focus mode, the H key will be typed as a value in the field. In contrast, while navigating through static content elsewhere in the document, the H key will cycle through the headings on the page and read each one aloud.

In rare scenarios, a widget that does not fall under any of the ARIA roles or patterns may need its own navigation paradigm. It is possible that role="application" could make the widget easier to use in NVDA or JAWS if the key commands MUST be passed through to the browser to function properly. But you better have a darn good reason and do adequate testing with screen reader users!
